# Line Plot

x = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)
y = np.sin(x)
plt.plot(x, y)
plt.title("Line Plot of Sine Wave")
plt.xlabel("X")
plt.ylabel("Sin(X)")
plt.show()

# Customizing Colors and Styles in Matplotlib
# You can set color palettes, line styles, and figure aesthetics for a professional look.

# Define data
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 100)
y1 = np.sin(x)
y2 = np.cos(x)

# Create a figure with size and customizations
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(x, y1, label="Sine", color="teal", linestyle="-", linewidth=2)
plt.plot(x, y2, label="Cosine", color="purple", linestyle="--", linewidth=2)
plt.xlabel("X Axis")
plt.ylabel("Values")
plt.title("Sine and Cosine Waves")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Using Seaborn’s FacetGrid for Multi-Plot Grids
# Useful for creating grids based on categorical data.

# Load data and create FacetGrid
df = sns.load_dataset("iris")
g = sns.FacetGrid(df, col="species", height=4)
g.map(sns.scatterplot, "sepal_length", "sepal_width")
plt.show()

# Adding Annotations for Extra Clarity
# Annotations can be a powerful way to highlight data points or trends.

# Highlighting a data point in a plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.lineplot(x=x, y=np.sin(x), label="Sine Wave")
plt.annotate("Peak", xy=(np.pi/2, 1), xytext=(2, 0.5),
             arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', arrowstyle="->"))
plt.title("Annotated Sine Wave Plot")
plt.show()
